		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A month later... PT 3.<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.62)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10224'>Lucas "skitch" Heath</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10224&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 3, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Raiders:<br />
Raiders bring a great element into the game, the element of surprise.  Many of the events in Raider decks are absolutely brutal, and that&#39;s a good thing.  &quot;A New Fear&quot; really kills superfellowships while Vision From Afar is also a great Burden Adder.  Easterlings really make Corruption a possibility.  One of my good friends came up with this idea for a deck: Sauron w/ Easterling corruption.  He uses Desperate Defense, Thin and Stretched, Vision From Afar and The Easterlings who exert when they are assigned to add burdens.  Add in a couple of New Fears and that will corrupt just about anyone.  Of course this strategy is very draw dependent as most bicultural shadows are, but if you catch someone at the right time, they can be very hard to beat.<br />
Easterlings can be very good on their own as well, the Skirmisher gives a swarm feel to this culture that can really hurt someone, but I feel as though Easterlings work best when combined with either Sauron or Nazgul.<br />
Southrons are just plain bad I feel... Maybe I am just not seeing it, but they are like Sauron except harder to play.  The best guys are the archers and the guys who exert to assign to the Ring-bearer but they have drawbacks as well.  Southrons in general have a few cards that key off site-control and burden adding, but they do neither very well.  For burdens they rely on Easterlings and Site Control, who knows?  The most playable Southron deck is probably direct exertions with those guys who remove 3 to wound a companion, but I don&#39;t see that being any better than a Orc Bowmen / Under the Watching Eye deck... once again I am probably just missing it, but I think Southrons are just not worth playing.  That said, I hope they get better because I think I have 2 or 3 of every rare Southron... they are all of course in my trading binder right now...<br />
<br />
Rohan:<br />
Eomer, Third Marshall of the Riddermark is the TT standard, the best card in the set.  BY FAR.  And being that, he sets the stage for the rest of the culture, a strong, versatile culture of 3 especially good companions and loads of good support cards.<br />
Each Companion brings a new element to the game, and each become extremely powerful:<br />
Eowyn:  True to form she is a powerful Lady and with her sword she becomes very powerful, but her game texts are what make her great.  The rare Eowyn provides throughput and a companion that barely ever dies while the common Eowyn is an answer to Enquea, Hate and Relentless Charge... she also adds twilight to the pool which is actually beneficial in a Gandalf deck.<br />
Eomer:  Sure, the common is almost not worth playing, but the rare makes up for it.  This guy is simply great.  With Firefoot and his Spear should really be considered the best companion in the game... He is basically a damage +4, defender +1, strength of about 11- 15 monster!  Who can compete with that?<br />
Theoden:  Theoden is a risky to use companion but very good nonetheless... to get good use out of him though, I think you need to play Gandalf and Hearken to me now, without that, Theoden is just too average to use.<br />
For support cards the best is obviously Simblemyne, which I believe is Decipher&#39;s first attempt at integrating Star Wars mechanics into the game, one of many to come.  I love Simblemyne&#39;s versatility, that&#39;s what makes it another banner card for Rohan.  Fortress Never Fallen is another great card because it changes the way condition removal is used.  I love the idea of a permanent that can get rid of cards and I also like the idea of making use out of winning skirmishes (especially when you have Eomer who almost never loses skirmishes, on your side).  I think though that the card or cards that will change the game from Rohan are the Mounts... Mounts are great even though they don&#39;t give strength bonuses, they are sure fire exertions and can provide quite a few bonuses like Brego&#39;s healing ability and Firefoots defender +1, plus they key cards like Helm! Helm! off, and are a load of fun to play with.  I think the anti-mount cards like Uruk Spear are a bit much because Mounts are only moderately powerful, but nonetheless Mounts bring a lot to the game.<br />
<br />
Sauron:<br />
Okay, okay, I know what you are thinking... Sauron sucked, and still sucks... and I pretty much agree with you, but I do think that Sauron can do damage if done right.  They like Nazgul and Easterlings form better decks in combinations between those three because combining the strengths of each gives you a more versatile pile.  The only card really worth discussing in Sauron is Enduring Evil, because it&#39;s still underated, and still can drastically change a game.  I think once Sauron gets its planned upgrade (better be a good one, like better site number maybe?) then Enduring Evil is going to get the respect it deserves, but until that day, just pray that someone pulls out &quot;Despair&quot; of your trading binder, and says... &quot;hmm... I need this card... what do you want for it&quot;...  (Tip: just give it to them... even a common foil like &quot;Orc Scimitar&quot; is just not a fair trade!)<br />
<br />
Shire:<br />
I already thought that the Shire was pretty strong before this set, but I think that it improved more than any other culture in the game.  The stealthy Hobbits are a great strategy, especially combined with the new Legolas.  I especially like Pippin, Just a Nuisance... combined with his wooden Friend, Pippin means one less Uruk per turn, and makes Uruk Vanguard worthless.  Granted he only hurts the Uruk-hai, but when he only hurts the most popular shadow culture by a mile, I think he&#39;s worth playing.  Merry on the otherhand is useless but that&#39;s another story.  I bet some of the Decipher people even remember making the moria card &quot;Fearing the Worst&quot; but it now effectively counters the best anti-Hobbit strategy in the game, not to mention hurts Sauron (from the who cares dept.).  The last thing I have to say about the unbound Hobbits is that it gives Hobbits the respectability they deserve... sure they can&#39;t fight like Aragorn, but they got what it takes to handle any situation.<br />
The only place Hobbits get hurt is the utter clobrinof the stealth cards... the next cards are about half as good as the originals because they do very little after site 5.  Severed his Bonds is good, but a good Hobbit deck is going to have Bounders, and Swiftly and Softly achieves what?  Hobbits don&#39;t really care about wounds... especially when they can discard themselves and play woundless next turn.<br />
The last area where Hobbits gain something is in the new cards that have old abilities but play a little differently.  Get on and Get Away is a great Thror&#39;s Map while Cliff&#39;s of Emyn Muil is the Power According that you don&#39;t have to hold all game.  Impatient and Angry is hilarious, and I can&#39;t wait to put it in my Promise deck (my absolute favorite deck-type EVER).  Frodo&#39;s cloak is also a permanent as is Sam&#39;s Pack which is the best new possession for the Shire... sure they have the cards that are pretty worthless:  see Brace of Coneys and Store-Room and the cards that are dissapointing like Sam, Frodo&#39;s Gardener (why do the rare Sam&#39;s ALWAYS suck) and rare Merry, but the Shire got better with this set, and I am very happy about that... Now all they need is something along the lines of <br />
Sam, Frodo&#39;s Protector:<br />
Strength: 3<br />
Vitality: 4<br />
Response: If Frodo takes a wound in a skirmish, Sam is Strength + 1 for each Burden you can spot until the Regroup phase.<br />
Lore: Sam loved his master, but don&#39;t say he&#39;s gay...<br />
<br />
In my Opinion:<br />
Strength Rankings Before TT:<br />
	Fellowship:		Shadow:<br />
1.	Gondor		Isengard<br />
2.	Elves			Moria<br />
3.	Shire			Nazgul<br />
4.	Gandalf		Sauron<br />
5.	Dwarves<br />
<br />
Strength Rankings After TT<br />
1.	Gondor		Isengard<br />
2.	Shire			Moria<br />
3.	Rohan		Dunland<br />
4.	Elves			Nazgul<br />
5.	Gandalf		Raiders<br />
6.	Dwarves		Sauron<br />
<br />
Notes:  <br />
 Raiders beat out Sauron because of Easterlings... If Southrons were their own category they&#39;d be dead last.<br />
 Isengard encompasses all the culture obviously but I believe some parts are stronger that others.  All of these except Isengard Orcs would still beat Moria, with Archery being the most powerful, followed by Isengard Trackers, Pure Beats and then Site Control.  Isengard Orcs would fall somewhere around Nazgul becuase I think if you played them right, they were actually quite effective.<br />
 Gandalf is low on both charts because he is really only good in multicultural decks...  Trust Decks for instance are very powerful and would be up there with the Shire and Rohan as the secondary power of Middle Earth.<br />
 Dunland is powerful assuming you have Hides x 3 or 4... otherwise it&#39;s just crap.<br />
 In some situations Moria tops the list, because if your deck is prepared to utterly destroy Uruk-hai, you probably can&#39;t last 4 or 5 sites against Moria.<br />
 Hobbits RULE!<br />
<br />
Thanks for reading... I can&#39;t believe you made it this far... I truly thank you though for listening to my thoughts on the new LOTR environment, and I thank you for any thoughts you may give in your reviews! <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=4232&view=1&PHPSESSID=a24151c39a985842f5899e7079ce8e74'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=a24151c39a985842f5899e7079ce8e74'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=a24151c39a985842f5899e7079ce8e74'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
